<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-309-977  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 309 977.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  Jan 1989 v14 n1 p267(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The data bandits. (data security issues) (In Depth - PCCommunications)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Adney, William M.; Kavanagh, Douglas E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Users of microcomputers that are connected to a local area network(LAN), and who store data on the file server should be concernedwith possible threats to data integrity.andP;  Potential threats tonetwork data include destructive programs such as viruses, TrojanHorse programs, Time Bombs, accidental destruction and theft ofinformation.andP;  Ways users can detect the presence of a virusinclude noticing that the infecting system or network will notperform normally, noticing if the drive light on a floppy or harddisk lights up frequently signalling disk activity when it is notin use, keeping an eye on the date of .COM and .EXE filesdisplayed by the DIR command, being familiar with what should beon the disk and what should not.andP;  Virus prevention methodsincludes not copying program files from bulletin boards,installing virus prevention software, use only originaldistribution shrink-wrapped software.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data SecurityComputer VirusesComputer CrimeData ManagementLocal Area Networks.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>